WEBVTT

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:15.710
Anyway, I started with Apple back in
February working on Motion,

00:00:15.710 --> 00:00:19.430
and if we could go to the
keynote machine please.

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:25.070
Motion was developed from
the ground up in OS X.

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:27.260
It was developed using Cocoa.

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:33.470
And as such, it has all the advantages of
the Unix architecture and the

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:36.400
OpenGL that goes along with that.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:39.640
But it's been a really great
environment to run in and to develop

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:42.400
motion graphics software for,
for a number of reasons,

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:45.400
because we need real time
performance in motion graphics.

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:47.400
We need to see what we're
doing as we're designing it.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:52.080
And it's traditionally been difficult
at best to get that type of performance,

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:54.400
except on very expensive hardware.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:58.400
So Motion, out of the box,
is set to--there we go.

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:00.400
Aimee Nugent's not here.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:02.400
I'm Kent Oberheu, in case we missed that.

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:06.100
But Motion is designed out of
the box to be a really high end

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:08.370
motion graphics application.

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:10.400
You can design in real time.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.240
You can see what you're
doing as you're doing it,

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:15.250
which is unprecedented for
the desktop environment.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:16.400
What are Motion Graphics?

00:01:16.490 --> 00:01:17.400
What are Motion Graphics?

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:18.370
What are Motion Graphics used for?

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:22.330
Well, they're used for titles for movies,
titles for DVD and video,

00:01:22.330 --> 00:01:25.120
motion titles that you
would use in DVD Studio Pro.

00:01:25.630 --> 00:01:29.720
They're also used for lower thirds,
which is a common term used

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.360
in news graphics and in
things like documentaries,

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:35.890
and where they, you know,
put the person's name and what

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:38.170
they do and how they're related.

00:01:38.530 --> 00:01:41.610
Graphics eye candy for raves and whatnot.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:44.710
So some of the advantages
of why motion is important,

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:48.030
and we'll start out,
first one here is scalable interface.

00:01:48.130 --> 00:01:50.700
We have a really scalable
interface from basic to advanced.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:54.690
What that means is we sort of unfold
the interface as you need to see it.

00:01:54.700 --> 00:01:57.700
We don't actually force you to
see all the controls at once.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:00.450
So to start off we have a really
simple toolbar sitting across

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:03.700
the top of the canvas which you
can't see entirely in this image.

00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:07.700
Layer view which allows
you to stack and composite,

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:10.800
and a file browser which is
really like the Mac OS X finder

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:12.590
built into the application.

00:02:12.710 --> 00:02:15.590
On the other side of the
screen we have the canvas,

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:18.520
which all is in one screen really,
which allows you to see

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:19.700
your composites as you work.

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:22.420
The dashboard which is
your on-screen controls,

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:25.830
it's a semi-transparent widget
that is context sensitive and

00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:29.090
updates with controls based on what
you're currently doing and which

00:02:29.090 --> 00:02:30.700
object you currently have active.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:33.680
You have a mini timeline which
is a little bit more complex.

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:35.600
It's collapsible so you don't
actually have to see the full

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:36.660
on timeline all the time.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:40.620
It sits across the bottom of your
workspace and allows you to see where

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:43.700
your object currently is active,
is sitting in time.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:45.700
It allows you to scrub as well, controls.

00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:49.700
And then of course the full on timeline
which shows you compositing and layers.

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:52.700
Our second key feature is
real time design engine.

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:55.760
Well the real time design engine,
what that allows you is a dynamic

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:58.700
real time design so you can see what
you're doing as you're doing it,

00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:01.980
get instant feedback that accelerates
filters so we can see what

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:02.630
filters are doing simultaneously.

00:03:02.760 --> 00:03:03.700
So that's a really cool feature.

00:03:03.700 --> 00:03:09.180
It even gives us the ability to
do live recording of animations.

00:03:09.330 --> 00:03:13.000
and of course scalable performance
based on whatever your hardware is.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.860
So if you've got a faster
graphics card you're going to

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:17.060
see that much better performance.

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:18.760
Next key feature is behaviors.

00:03:18.890 --> 00:03:19.670
What are behaviors?

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:22.370
Well,
behaviors are procedural based animation.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:25.710
They're actually objects that
connect to another object that say,

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:30.200
"You do this over this time,"
or "You do this over this time."

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:32.900
Simple things from fade in,
fade out, to spinning,

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:35.490
to advanced things like
simulation behaviors where we

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:40.870
have gravity and wind interacting,
collision detection and things like that.

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:45.240
and it allows you to interact with
multiple behaviors simultaneously,

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:46.590
so you can even stack these behaviors.

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:49.170
We'll go through that a little
later in the presentation.

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:51.200
The next key feature is integration.

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:54.930
How do we integrate with
the Apple Pro lineup?

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:56.490
Well, it's actually really incredible.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:01.550
We have XML export straight from
Final Cut Pro that will actually

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:05.940
save a motion file from your entire
timeline or a portion of your timeline,

00:04:06.010 --> 00:04:08.590
opens directly in motion,
it's not importing,

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:12.430
it just is a motion file that opens,
allows you to move objects around,

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:15.780
add text, add filters,
add different composite modes,

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:19.510
different translations to these things,
and then you can save that,

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:22.900
and immediately that is visible
in the Final Cut Pro timeline.

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:24.890
The same thing works with DVD Studio Pro.

00:04:25.170 --> 00:04:26.600
You don't even have to
render these things.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:31.080
You can just take a .iomo.tn file and
just open that up in DVD Studio Pro,

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:33.270
make changes, update it instantly.

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:35.030
Of course,
you can do your final export to tape

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:40.640
or to disk or you're burning your disk,
it does the rendering at the same time.

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:42.600
Some of the feature highlights.

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:45.480
So I mentioned earlier the user
interface design is rather innovative.

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.040
We've got a dashboard, semi-transparent.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:49.650
You probably saw the
Mac OS X Tiger dashboard

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:51.100
that comes with widgets.

